TITLE: Using Lo's Parallel Map Function for Concurrent Processing
DESCRIPTION: Example demonstrating the parallel version of Map function which processes elements concurrently in goroutines while maintaining the original order in the result.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_6

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
import lop "github.com/samber/lo/parallel"

lop.Map([]int64{1, 2, 3, 4}, func(x int64, _ int) string {
    return strconv.FormatInt(x, 10)
})
// []string{"1", "2", "3", "4"}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Function Retry in Go with Attempt
DESCRIPTION: Attempt invokes a function repeatedly until it succeeds or reaches a maximum number of attempts. Returns the iteration count and error (if any).
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_198

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
iter, err := lo.Attempt(42, func(i int) error {
    if i == 5 {
        return nil
    }

    return fmt.Errorf("failed")
})
// 6
// nil

iter, err := lo.Attempt(2, func(i int) error {
    if i == 5 {
        return nil
    }

    return fmt.Errorf("failed")
})
// 2
// error "failed"

iter, err := lo.Attempt(0, func(i int) error {
    if i < 42 {
        return fmt.Errorf("failed")
    }

    return nil
})
// 43
// nil
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Using Lo's Map Function to Transform Types
DESCRIPTION: Example showing how to use Lo's Map function to transform a slice of int64 values into string representations. The mapper function receives both the element and its index.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_5

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
import "github.com/samber/lo"

lo.Map([]int64{1, 2, 3, 4}, func(x int64, index int) string {
    return strconv.FormatInt(x, 10)
})
// []string{"1", "2", "3", "4"}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Checking for Nil Values with IsNil in Go
DESCRIPTION: Checks if a value is nil or if it's a reference type with a nil underlying value. Works with interfaces that contain nil values, which is different from a direct nil check.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_175

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
var x int
lo.IsNil(x)
// false

var k struct{}
lo.IsNil(k)
// false

var i *int
lo.IsNil(i)
// true

var ifaceWithNilValue any = (*string)(nil)
lo.IsNil(ifaceWithNilValue)
// true
ifaceWithNilValue == nil
// false
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Implementing Saga Pattern Transactions in Go
DESCRIPTION: Implements the Saga pattern for distributed transactions with compensation actions for rollback.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_207

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
transaction := NewTransaction().
    Then(
        func(state int) (int, error) {
            fmt.Println("step 1")
            return state + 10, nil
        },
        func(state int) int {
            fmt.Println("rollback 1")
            return state - 10
        },
    )
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Implementing Generator Pattern in Go with Lo Library
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to implement the generator design pattern using the Generator function.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_108

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
generator := func(yield func(int)) {
    yield(1)
    yield(2)
    yield(3)
}

for v := range lo.Generator(2, generator) {
    println(v)
}
// prints 1, then 2, then 3
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Debouncing Functions in Go with NewDebounce
DESCRIPTION: NewDebounce creates a debounced function that delays invoking the provided function until after a specified wait time has elapsed since the last call. Returns the debounced function and a cancel function.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_202

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
f := func() {
    println("Called once after 100ms when debounce stopped invoking!")
}

debounce, cancel := lo.NewDebounce(100 * time.Millisecond, f)
for j := 0; j < 10; j++ {
    debounce()
}

time.Sleep(1 * time.Second)
cancel()
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Implementing Ternary Operation with Functions in Go
DESCRIPTION: Provides a one-line if/else statement functionality with function options. Evaluates only the function corresponding to the condition result, which helps avoid nil-pointer dereferencing or unnecessary code execution.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_167

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
result := lo.TernaryF(true, func() string { return "a" }, func() string { return "b" })
// "a"

result := lo.TernaryF(false, func() string { return "a" }, func() string { return "b" })
// "b"
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Polling with WaitFor Functions in Go
DESCRIPTION: Implements polling functionality to periodically check conditions with timeout support and context cancellation.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_208

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
iterations, duration, ok := lo.WaitFor(alwaysTrue, 10*time.Millisecond, 2 * time.Millisecond)
// 1
// 1ms
// true

iterations, duration, ok := lo.WaitFor(alwaysFalse, 10*time.Millisecond, time.Millisecond)
// 10 
// 10ms
// false
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Merging Multiple Maps in Go
DESCRIPTION: Assign merges multiple maps from left to right, with later maps' values taking precedence over earlier ones in case of key collisions. This is useful for combining configuration or parameter maps.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_71

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
mergedMaps := lo.Assign(
    map[string]int{"a": 1, "b": 2},
    map[string]int{"b": 3, "c": 4},
)
// map[string]int{"a": 1, "b": 3, "c": 4}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Using Reduce for Slice Operations in Go
DESCRIPTION: Reduce combines slice elements into a single value by applying an accumulator function to each element. Each invocation receives the previous accumulated value.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_10

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
sum := lo.Reduce([]int{1, 2, 3, 4}, func(agg int, item int, _ int) int {
    return agg + item
}, 0)
// 10
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Implementing If-ElseIf-Else Chain in Go
DESCRIPTION: Provides a fluent API for if/elseif/else conditional logic, returning the value associated with the first true condition or the else value if no conditions are met.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_169

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
result := lo.If(true, 1).
    ElseIf(false, 2).
    Else(3)
// 1

result := lo.If(false, 1).
    ElseIf(true, 2).
    Else(3)
// 2

result := lo.If(false, 1).
    ElseIf(false, 2).
    Else(3)
// 3
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Implementing Switch-Case-Default with Functions in Go
DESCRIPTION: Provides a fluent API for switch/case/default conditional logic with function callbacks, evaluating only the function associated with the matching case or the default function if no cases match.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_173

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
result := lo.Switch(1).
    CaseF(1, func() string {
        return "1"
    }).
    CaseF(2, func() string {
        return "2"
    }).
    DefaultF(func() string {
        return "3"
    })
// "1"
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Conditional Function Retry in Go with AttemptWhile
DESCRIPTION: AttemptWhile invokes a function repeatedly with early termination capability based on the second boolean return value. Continues until success, max attempts, or explicit termination.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_200

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
count1, err1 := lo.AttemptWhile(5, func(i int) (error, bool) {
    err := doMockedHTTPRequest(i)
    if err != nil {
        if errors.Is(err, ErrBadRequest) { // lets assume ErrBadRequest is a critical error that needs to terminate the invoke
            return err, false // flag the second return value as false to terminate the invoke
        }

        return err, true
    }

    return nil, false
})
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Function Retry with Delay in Go using AttemptWithDelay
DESCRIPTION: AttemptWithDelay invokes a function repeatedly with a specified delay between attempts until it succeeds or reaches a maximum number of attempts. Returns iteration count, duration, and error (if any).
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_199

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
iter, duration, err := lo.AttemptWithDelay(5, 2*time.Second, func(i int, duration time.Duration) error {
    if i == 2 {
        return nil
    }

    return fmt.Errorf("failed")
})
// 3
// ~ 4 seconds
// nil
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Executing Async Operations with Channels in Go
DESCRIPTION: Launches functions asynchronously in goroutines and returns results through channels. Supports functions with 0-6 return values.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_206

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
ch := lo.Async0(func() { time.Sleep(10 * time.Second) })
// chan struct{}

ch := lo.Async1(func() int {
  time.Sleep(10 * time.Second);
  return 42
})
// chan int (42)

ch := lo.Async2(func() (int, string) {
  time.Sleep(10 * time.Second);
  return 42, "Hello"
})
// chan lo.Tuple2[int, string] ({42, "Hello"})
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Dereferencing Pointers with Fallback using FromPtrOr in Go
DESCRIPTION: Returns the pointer value or a specified fallback value if the pointer is nil. Provides a safe way to dereference pointers with custom fallback values.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_181

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
str := "hello world"
value := lo.FromPtrOr(&str, "empty")
// "hello world"

value := lo.FromPtrOr(nil, "empty")
// "empty"
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Throttling Function Calls in Go with Throttle Functions
DESCRIPTION: Various throttle functions that limit execution frequency for operations. Includes basic throttling, count-limited throttling, and key-based throttling variants.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_204

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
f := func() {
	println("Called once in every 100ms")
}

throttle, reset := lo.NewThrottle(100 * time.Millisecond, f)

for j := 0; j < 10; j++ {
	throttle()
	time.Sleep(30 * time.Millisecond)
}

reset()
throttle()
```

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
f := func() {
	println("Called three times in every 100ms")
}

throttle, reset := lo.NewThrottleWithCount(100 * time.Millisecond, f)

for j := 0; j < 10; j++ {
	throttle()
	time.Sleep(30 * time.Millisecond)
}

reset()
throttle()
```

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
f := func(key string) {
	println(key, "Called three times in every 100ms")
}

throttle, reset := lo.NewThrottleByWithCount(100 * time.Millisecond, f)

for j := 0; j < 10; j++ {
	throttle("foo")
	time.Sleep(30 * time.Millisecond)
}

reset()
throttle()
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Using FilterMap for Slices in Go
DESCRIPTION: FilterMap returns a new slice after both filtering and mapping using a callback function. The callback returns both the mapped value and a boolean indicating inclusion.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_8

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
matching := lo.FilterMap([]string{"cpu", "gpu", "mouse", "keyboard"}, func(x string, _ int) (string, bool) {
    if strings.HasSuffix(x, "pu") {
        return "xpu", true
    }
    return "", false
})
// []string{"xpu", "xpu"}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Using Parallel ForEach for Slice Iteration in Go
DESCRIPTION: The parallel version of ForEach processes each element in a goroutine, enabling concurrent execution but with non-deterministic order of processing.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_13

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
import lop "github.com/samber/lo/parallel"

lop.ForEach([]string{"hello", "world"}, func(x string, _ int) {
    println(x)
})
// prints "hello\nworld\n" or "world\nhello\n"
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Broadcasting Channel Messages in Go with Lo Library
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to broadcast all upstream messages to multiple downstream channels using the FanOut function.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_113

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
stream := make(chan int, 42)

all := lo.FanOut(5, 100, stream)
// [5]<-chan int
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Implementing Mutex-Based Synchronization in Go
DESCRIPTION: Wraps callbacks in a mutex for sequential execution. Provides synchronized access to shared resources across goroutines.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_205

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
s := lo.Synchronize()

for i := 0; i < 10; i++ {
    go s.Do(func () {
        println("will be called sequentially")
    })
}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Creating a Set with Keyify in Go
DESCRIPTION: Converts a slice to a map where each unique element becomes a key with an empty struct as value, essentially creating a set data structure.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_35

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
set := lo.Keyify([]int{1, 1, 2, 3, 4})
// map[int]struct{}{1:{}, 2:{}, 3:{}, 4:{}}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Implementing If-ElseIf-Else Chain with Functions in Go
DESCRIPTION: Provides a fluent API for if/elseif/else conditional logic with function callbacks, evaluating only the function associated with the first true condition or the else function if no conditions are met.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_170

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
result := lo.IfF(true, func () int {
        return 1
    }).
    ElseIfF(false, func () int {
        return 2
    }).
    ElseF(func () int {
        return 3
    })
// 1
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Implementing Ternary Operation in Go
DESCRIPTION: Provides a one-line if/else statement functionality. Returns the first value if the condition is true, otherwise returns the second value. Both expressions are evaluated regardless of the condition.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_166

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
result := lo.Ternary(true, "a", "b")
// "a"

result := lo.Ternary(false, "a", "b")
// "b"
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Conditional Function Retry with Delay in Go using AttemptWhileWithDelay
DESCRIPTION: AttemptWhileWithDelay invokes a function repeatedly with delays and early termination capability. Continues until success, max attempts, or explicit termination.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_201

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
count1, time1, err1 := lo.AttemptWhileWithDelay(5, time.Millisecond, func(i int, d time.Duration) (error, bool) {
    err := doMockedHTTPRequest(i)
    if err != nil {
        if errors.Is(err, ErrBadRequest) { // lets assume ErrBadRequest is a critical error that needs to terminate the invoke
            return err, false // flag the second return value as false to terminate the invoke
        }

        return err, true
    }

    return nil, false
})
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Implementing Switch-Case-Default in Go
DESCRIPTION: Provides a fluent API for switch/case/default conditional logic, returning the value associated with the matching case or the default value if no cases match.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_172

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
result := lo.Switch(1).
    Case(1, "1").
    Case(2, "2").
    Default("3")
// "1"

result := lo.Switch(2).
    Case(1, "1").
    Case(2, "2").
    Default("3")
// "2"

result := lo.Switch(42).
    Case(1, "1").
    Case(2, "2").
    Default("3")
// "3"
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Using GroupBy for Slice Categorization in Go
DESCRIPTION: GroupBy creates a map of grouped elements based on a key generated by the iteratee function. Elements with the same key are grouped together in an array.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_19

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
import lo "github.com/samber/lo"

groups := lo.GroupBy([]int{0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5}, func(i int) int {
    return i%3
})
// map[int][]int{0: []int{0, 3}, 1: []int{1, 4}, 2: []int{2, 5}}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Using Find to search for an element using a predicate in Go
DESCRIPTION: Find searches an element in a slice based on a predicate. It returns the element and true if the element was found, otherwise it returns the zero value and false.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_131

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
str, ok := lo.Find([]string{"a", "b", "c", "d"}, func(i string) bool {
    return i == "b"
})
// "b", true

str, ok := lo.Find([]string{"foobar"}, func(i string) bool {
    return i == "b"
})
// "", false
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Using GroupByMap for Slice Categorization with Value Transformation in Go
DESCRIPTION: GroupByMap creates a map of grouped elements, allowing both key generation and value transformation through the iteratee function.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_21

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
import lo "github.com/samber/lo"

groups := lo.GroupByMap([]int{0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5}, func(i int) (int, int) {
    return i%3, i*2
})
// map[int][]int{0: []int{0, 6}, 1: []int{2, 8}, 2: []int{4, 10}}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Partial Function Application in Go with Partial
DESCRIPTION: Partial returns a new function with its first argument preset to a provided value. This implements basic currying/partial application functionality.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_196

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
add := func(x, y int) int { return x + y }
f := lo.Partial(add, 5)

f(10)
// 15

f(42)
// 47
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Using KeyBy for Converting Slices to Maps in Go
DESCRIPTION: KeyBy transforms a slice into a map where the keys are determined by a callback function. This enables efficient lookups based on specific attributes of the elements.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_32

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
m := lo.KeyBy([]string{"a", "aa", "aaa"}, func(str string) int {
    return len(str)
})
// map[int]string{1: "a", 2: "aa", 3: "aaa"}

type Character struct {
  dir  string
  code int
}
characters := []Character{
    {dir: "left", code: 97},
    {dir: "right", code: 100},
}
result := lo.KeyBy(characters, func(char Character) string {
    return string(rune(char.code))
})
//map[a:{dir:left code:97} d:{dir:right code:100}]
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Using Lo's Filter Function with Integer Slices
DESCRIPTION: Example demonstrating Lo's Filter function to select even numbers from an integer slice. The predicate function takes both the element and its index as parameters.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
even := lo.Filter([]int{1, 2, 3, 4}, func(x int, index int) bool {
    return x%2 == 0
})
// []int{2, 4}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Installing Lo Library in Go
DESCRIPTION: This snippet shows how to install the Lo library using the go get command. It demonstrates the command to fetch and install the library from the GitHub repository.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/img/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: shell
CODE:
```
go get github.com/samber/lo
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Converting Slices to Pointer Slices with ToSlicePtr in Go
DESCRIPTION: Returns a slice of pointer copies for each value in the input slice. Useful for converting value slices to pointer slices.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_182

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
ptr := lo.ToSlicePtr([]string{"hello", "world"})
// []*string{"hello", "world"}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Extended Partial Function Application in Go with Partial2-5
DESCRIPTION: Partial2 through Partial5 provide partial application for functions with more parameters, allowing fixing the first parameter's value and returning a new function.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_197

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
add := func(x, y, z int) int { return x + y + z }
f := lo.Partial2(add, 42)

f(10, 5)
// 57

f(42, -4)
// 80
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Creating Pointers from Values with ToPtr in Go
DESCRIPTION: Returns a pointer copy of the given value, useful for quickly creating pointers to values without separate variable declarations.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_177

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
ptr := lo.ToPtr("hello world")
// *string{"hello world"}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Merging Multiple Channels in Go with Lo Library
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to merge messages from multiple input channels into a single buffered channel using the FanIn function.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_112

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
stream1 := make(chan int, 42)
stream2 := make(chan int, 42)
stream3 := make(chan int, 42)

all := lo.FanIn(100, stream1, stream2, stream3)
// <-chan int
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Importing and Using Lo Library in Go
DESCRIPTION: This code snippet demonstrates how to import and use the Lo library in a Go program. It shows the import statement and a basic example of using the Filter function from the library.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/img/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
import (
    "github.com/samber/lo"
    "github.com/samber/lo/parallel"
)

even := lo.Filter([]int{1, 2, 3, 4}, func(x int, _ int) bool {
    return x%2 == 0
})
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Using Some to check if any elements of a subset exist in a collection in Go
DESCRIPTION: Some returns true if at least one element of a subset is contained in a collection. If the subset is empty, Some returns false. It checks for any overlap between two slices.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_118

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
ok := lo.Some([]int{0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5}, []int{0, 6})
// true

ok := lo.Some([]int{0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5}, []int{-1, 6})
// false
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Checking Element Presence in Collection in Go with Lo Library
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to check if an element is present in a collection using the Contains function.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_114

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
present := lo.Contains([]int{0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5}, 5)
// true
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Buffering Channel Data in Go with Lo Library
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to create a slice of n elements from a channel using the Buffer function.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_109

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
ch := lo.SliceToChannel(2, []int{1, 2, 3, 4, 5})

items1, length1, duration1, ok1 := lo.Buffer(ch, 3)
// []int{1, 2, 3}, 3, 0s, true
items2, length2, duration2, ok2 := lo.Buffer(ch, 3)
// []int{4, 5}, 2, 0s, false
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Channel Dispatcher in Go with Lo Library
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to distribute messages from input channels into multiple child channels using the ChannelDispatcher function.
SOURCE: https://github.com/samber/lo/blob/master/README.md#2025-04-22_snippet_105

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
ch := make(chan int, 42)
for i := 0; i <= 10; i++ {
    ch <- i
}

children := lo.ChannelDispatcher(ch, 5, 10, DispatchingStrategyRoundRobin[int])
// []<-chan int{...}

consumer := func(c <-chan int) {
    for {
        msg, ok := <-c
        if !ok {
            println("closed")

            break
        }

        println(msg)
    }
}

for i := range children {
    go consumer(children[i])
}
```

